<HR size="1" color="#000000">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The gains do thin past 70, they dont stop immediately but after a period you stop getting attribute points and then after that I belive you stop getting skill points, or maybe only 1 per level.  Once you reach this point leveling is a prestige thing.  You can say I have a level 100 character, of course most people wont really care unless you got those last 30 levels whacking players around your level.<P>I think if you take a look at the PvP system you will see what will happen abouta month after most players hit the soft cap.  <P>Every PvP encounter ends up being a net loss of exp.  Sure the winner gets some exp and the defeated looses some but he looses more than the other guy gains.  So all those 90% of the people that stop leveling will go around and kill each other hundreds of times in guildwars etc and soon find themselves in need of exp to get their skills back.  <P>Also since you need lots and lots of money to run a big city and the only way to get money is to kill monsters you will probably have to go around and trounce monsters to raise money for your guild.<P>If the value of leveling didn't stop the game would probably turn into another EQ because you would NEED to go out and level for your guild to be competetive.  Then it would just turn into a level race.  Who can get the most level 200's the fastest and own everyone else ... in my book, LAME.<P>I really really really like the idea that level differences mean less and less at higher levels because of the idea of diminishing returns.  That way my level 70 has a good chance against a level 90 but I may back down from a fight because he is level 90 and prolly knows what he is doing.  But if it comes down to a large battle and I am forced to do combat with characters 10 or 15 levels above me I have a chance.<P>I dont think much of the stuff to do after you stop leveling will get old besides farming monsters for cash.  Fighting other players always presents unique and interesting situations.  I mean take a look at some first person shooters like Counter-Strike or Unreal Tournament.  People have been playing those games with the same weapons on the same levels for years but because they are playing against humans and every game is different.<P>--------------------<P>Certa<BR><A HREF="http://sb.castersrealm.com" TARGET=_blank> <IMG SRC="http://cec.wustl.edu/~dhg1/sbr_banner.gif"> </A><BR>-The pure blood of my ancient elven ancestors courses through my veins, tainted though it may be. One day I will cleanse the taint of humanity from my body, my soul, and then the world.
</FONT>
